The paper proposes a novel framework for network embedding that focuses on domain adaptation, which is a common problem in machine learning. The paper uses graph convolutional networks to learn transferable embeddings, which is a popular technique in the field of deep learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also discusses the use of adversarial learning regularization, which is a technique commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) and computer vision (CV), suggesting that cs.CL (Computation and Language) may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper focuses on network embedding, which is a subfield of graph theory, suggesting that cs.NE (Networks and Internet Architecture) may also be a relevant sub-category.
